# AKOS Deploy Health — recurrent CICD smoke discipline

> Codifies the recurrent pattern for verifying that **any consumer repo tracked in `REPOSITORY_REGISTRY.csv`** deploys + renders correctly after meaningful changes. **This is a runtime / pre-merge discipline**, distinct from design-time skills like Impeccable. Established during I66 P5 (2026-05-09 build-fix incident) and intended to apply to all current and future Holistika consumer repos: web frontends, internal operator surfaces, public APIs, agentic systems, and any deployable artefact governed by the AKOS bless pattern.

## Why a separate rule

Three (now four) different concerns, three different tools:

| Concern | Tool | When it runs |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Design-time** (page authoring, brand alignment, voice tier) | [`impeccable` skill](../../.cursor/skills/impeccable/SKILL.md) — uses `PRODUCT.md`, `DESIGN.md`, `BASELINE_REALITY.md` | When a page or component is being designed or rewritten |
| **Pre-merge automated regression** (build, type, lint, e2e) | Per-repo Playwright/Jest/Vitest suite + Lighthouse + brand drift gates | Every PR + every push to a feature branch |
| **Pre-merge operator UAT** (visual smoke + UX judgement) | Browser-use subagent + operator manual check | Before operator review of a PR or significant change |
| **Continuous deploy health** | Hosting-platform MCP polling (Vercel, Render, etc.) | At start of every operator turn that touches a consumer repo |
| **Visual regression** (future I-NN initiative) | Percy / Argos / Chromatic — see [`docs/wip/planning/68-cicd-scalability-and-visual-regression/master-roadmap.md`](../../docs/wip/planning/68-cicd-scalability-and-visual-regression/master-roadmap.md) | Per-PR (chartered I68; pending launch) |

Impeccable answers "is this page designed well?" — NOT "did the deploy succeed?" or "does it work on mobile?". Use the right tool for the right question.

## Standard CICD smoke checklist (run at start of every consumer-repo turn)

### Step 1 — Deploy status check (≤ 2 min)

For every consumer repo touched in the current session, poll the relevant hosting platform's MCP. The repo-to-platform mapping is the source of truth in [`REPOSITORY_REGISTRY.csv`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Envoy%20Tech%20Lab/Repositories/REPOSITORY_REGISTRY.csv) (column: `hosting_platform`). Common platforms and their MCP polling tools:

- **Vercel** (Next.js / static frontends): `list_deployments(teamId, projectId, limit=5)`
- **Render** (backends, workers, Postgres, static sites): `list_deploys(serviceId, limit=5)`
- **Other** (GitHub Pages, Cloudflare, AWS, etc.): document polling tool when added.

Flag if any of the last 5 deployments are **terminal-error** (`ERROR` on Vercel, `failed` / `update_failed` on Render, equivalent elsewhere). Heuristic — three or more consecutive terminal-errors usually means a code regression that's blocking everyone, not a transient infra issue.

### Step 2 — Build log inspection on failure (≤ 5 min)

If the most recent deploy is terminal-error, fetch + parse the build log:

- **Vercel**: `get_deployment_build_logs(teamId, idOrUrl, limit=400)`
- **Render**: `list_logs(serviceId, deployId, limit=400)`

Look in the **last ~30 events** for the actual error trail (the first events are typically clone + dep-install warnings, which are noise). See §"Common build failures" below for the catalogue of known patterns + canonical fixes.

### Step 3 — Visual smoke (≤ 15 min)

After a successful deploy, run a multi-viewport visual smoke via the **browser-use subagent**. Standard viewports — apply judgement; not every repo needs all of them (e.g., backend-only services skip this entirely):

- **375 × 667** (iPhone SE) — narrowest mobile common case.
- **414 × 896** (iPhone 11 / 12 / 13 / 14 / 15) — wider mobile.
- **768 × 1024** (iPad portrait) — tablet.
- **1280 × 800** (desktop default) — most-common laptop.
- **1920 × 1080** (wide desktop) — large monitor.

The subagent prompt should explicitly enumerate:

1. Pages or routes to load + key elements to verify (relative to the change being shipped).
2. Locale switching where applicable (per-repo `i18n` configuration).
3. Console errors / 404s (cumulative).
4. Mobile-specific overflow / overlap / illegibility checks.
5. Auth state (preview deployments may be behind Vercel Authentication / similar — pass session credentials or operator-pre-authenticated browser tab).

Report format: HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW severity findings; actionable remediation per finding. Skimmable for operator review.

### Step 4 — Build-time optimization gates

Maintain build-time discipline. Operator's stated target: **< 2 min per preview build** for typical frontend repos.

If preview build > 2 min, profile the build log timestamps:

- Clone time
- Dependency install time (note total package count)
- Compile time (the typical bottleneck)
- Type-check time (if any)
- Static-prerender or generation time
- Source-map upload time (if observability provider integrated)

Then apply targeted optimizations per platform / framework:

- **Source-map upload to observability vendors** (Sentry, Datadog, etc.): make non-blocking + skip on previews; restrict to production builds only.
- **Stale build cache**: ensure the cache is restored across deploys. Any "fresh dependency install" line means the cache was missed.
- **Static prerender of dynamic routes**: use route-segment `force-dynamic` + lazy-init pattern (see Failure 3 below).
- **Framework-level**: Next.js Turbopack opt-in (14+); Vite for SPAs; SWC over Babel; etc.
- **Single slow page**: profile that page's data-fetching pattern (avoid blocking server fetches at build time).

## Common build failures + canonical fixes

Catalogued from real incidents. **When a new failure mode is encountered, append a Failure N entry below.** Each entry should specify: symptom (the error message you'll see in logs), root cause (the why), canonical fix (the recommended remediation), framework-applicability (where this pattern matters).

### Failure 1 — Duplicate `declare global { interface Window { ... } }`

**Framework**: TypeScript projects (any framework).

**Symptom**: `Property 'X' does not exist on type '(...args: unknown[]) => void'` or similar declaration-merging error during `tsc` / `next build` / `vite build`.

**Root cause**: Two or more files declare `Window.X` (or any global type) with incompatible shapes. TypeScript's declaration merging produces an intersection that loses methods or properties.

**Canonical fix**: One canonical declaration in a project-root `types/global.d.ts` (or equivalent — `src/types/`, `app/types/`, etc.). Remove all per-component `declare global` blocks. Ensure the types directory is in `tsconfig.json` `include`.

### Failure 2 — Observability SDK CLI fails build (e.g. Sentry, Datadog) on transient API error

**Framework**: any project that uploads source maps / release artefacts during build.

**Symptom**: `unhandledRejection Error: Command failed: ... <vendor>-cli releases new <SHA>` followed by `Error: Command "<build cmd>" exited with 1`. Often a 504/5xx from the vendor's API.

**Root cause**: Transient outage during source-map / release upload. Should NOT block the build.

**Canonical fix**: Two changes per platform's webpack/build plugin:

1. Add a non-blocking error handler that logs the error as a warning instead of failing the build.
2. Skip source-map upload on **preview / non-production** environments via the platform's environment indicator (e.g., `process.env.VERCEL_ENV !== 'production'`, `process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production'`, etc.). Production builds still upload.

### Failure 3 — Static prerender fails on data-source-dependent route

**Framework**: Next.js / Remix / SvelteKit / any framework with build-time prerender.

**Symptom**: `Error occurred prerendering page "..."` followed by an error from a database / auth / API client (e.g., "URL and Key are required to create a client").

**Root cause**: Module-level instantiation of a client (e.g., `const queries = new XQueries();`) runs at build-time prerender even with `"use client"` / framework-specific dynamic flags, because the bundler still loads the module to extract route-segment configuration.

**Canonical fix** (cleanest): Replace module-level instantiation with a lazy singleton getter:

```ts
let _client: XQueries | null = null;
function getClient(): XQueries {
  if (!_client) _client = new XQueries();
  return _client;
}

export default function Page() {
  const client = getClient();  // called only on render
  // ...
}
```

Route-segment `force-dynamic` (Next.js) / equivalent **alone is not sufficient** — the bundler still evaluates module-level code during route-segment-config extraction.

### Failure 4 — Mobile navbar overflow / no hamburger

**Framework**: web frontends with a top navigation bar.

**Symptom**: Operator (or visual smoke test) reports navbar links squeezed horizontally on viewports ≤ 768 px, no hamburger menu.

**Canonical fix**: Two-pattern navbar — `hidden md:flex` (or framework equivalent) for inline desktop, `flex md:hidden` for compact mobile pill with hamburger button + slide-down drawer. The mobile pill should auto-close the drawer on scroll-down or link tap.

### Failure 5 — Sticky secondary header overlapping primary navbar on mobile

**Framework**: web frontends with a sticky / fixed primary navbar AND a route-level sticky sub-header (article reader, breadcrumb, action bar).

**Symptom**: A sticky `top-0` secondary header overlaps with the primary navbar on mobile because the primary navbar wraps to multiple lines or has different intrinsic height across breakpoints.

**Canonical fix**:

- (a) Fix the primary navbar to be compact on mobile (Failure 4 fix).
- (b) Adjust the secondary header's top-padding to be breakpoint-responsive (e.g., `pt-16 md:pt-20` — mobile gets less because the navbar pill is shorter).
- (c) Hide UX-context-dependent actions (share, bookmark — anything requiring auth) below the `sm` breakpoint: `hidden sm:flex`.

### Failure 6 (speculative; awaits P3 confirmation) — Visual-regression false positive on font subpixel rendering across CI runners

**Framework**: any project using a visual-regression vendor (Argos / Lost Pixel / Percy / Chromatic) with Playwright + multi-viewport snapshots.

**Symptom**: Visual-regression vendor flags pixel diffs on text-heavy regions across runs even when no UI code changed. Diff regions are restricted to text edges; non-text regions match. Reproduces inconsistently across runs (sometimes greenish, sometimes flagged).

**Root cause**: GitHub Actions runners (`ubuntu-latest`) have non-deterministic font subpixel positioning depending on the runner's underlying VM build. Anti-aliasing differs at the sub-pixel level; the vendor's diff threshold detects these as changes.

**Canonical fix**: Add `--disable-font-subpixel-positioning` to the Chromium launch args for **visual-regression projects only** (not for functional Playwright tests, where this flag would mask real regressions). Reference: `_templates/playwright.config.ts.tmpl` (P2 deliverable) projects array entry for visual-regression. If the vendor offers an "ignore anti-aliasing" threshold, prefer that as the primary mitigation; this flag is the fallback when the vendor lacks the option.

**Status**: Speculative — added at I68 P8 from the charter §P8 "speculative Failure-N entries" list. Promotes to confirmed when first observed in real CI on the P3 visual-regression rollout (`boilerplate` first; gated at PAUSE POINT #2). On confirmation, replace the "Speculative" line with an incident date + commit SHA + run URL.

### Failure 7 (speculative; awaits P6 confirmation) — Render auto-deploy timeout on cold-start of a fresh worker

**Framework**: Render-hosted services with `numInstances: 1` (no scale-to-zero) on a Starter or Standard plan.

**Symptom**: First request to a freshly-deployed Render worker times out after ~30s. Render dashboard shows the deploy as "Live" but the healthcheck endpoint never responded in the deploy-completion window. Subsequent requests succeed once the worker has spun up.

**Root cause**: Render's deploy completion is tied to the healthcheck endpoint responding within the deploy-completion timeout. If `healthCheckPath` is unset or set to a route that triggers cold-start work (e.g., loading a heavy ML model on first invocation), the healthcheck fails before the worker is ready.

**Canonical fix**: Set `healthCheckPath` explicitly in `render.yaml` to a lightweight endpoint (`/health` returning `200 OK` with the release-format JSON `{"release": "<repo>@<sha-short>", "ok": true}`) that does **not** trigger cold-start work. Reference: `_templates/render/render-baseline.yaml.tmpl` (P5 deliverable) for the canonical pattern. For services that genuinely need cold-start work for the first request, increase `healthCheckTimeout` to accommodate the cold-start budget (Render allows up to 5 min) AND ensure the healthcheck route remains separate from the cold-start-heavy routes.

**Status**: Speculative — added at I68 P8 from the charter §P8 "speculative Failure-N entries" list. Promotes to confirmed when first observed in real Render deploys during P6 build-time optimization sweep on `kirbe-platform` (gated; requires Render MCP API calls). On confirmation, replace the "Speculative" line with an incident date + commit SHA + Render service ID.

### Adding new failure modes

When you encounter a new build / deploy failure pattern:

1. Reproduce it in the build log.
2. Add a new `### Failure N — <one-line title>` section below following the same template (Framework / Symptom / Root cause / Canonical fix).
3. Reference any reusable template files in the consumer repo (e.g., a config snippet) by **path**, not by full content — the rule should stay reasonably short.
4. Update the I66 P5 ChangeLog entry list (or wherever the historical incident is logged) with a back-reference.

